1. pwd – shows your current directory (“print working directory”).

2. ls – lists the files and folders in the current directory. Try ls -l for details and ls -a to see hidden files.

3. cd <directory> – changes to another directory. cd .. goes up one level, and cd ~ returns to your home folder.

4. mkdir project1 – creates a new folder.

5. touch notes.txt – creates an empty file.

6. cp source destination – copies a file or folder (-r is needed for folders).

7. mv old new – moves or renames a file.

8. rm file and rm -r folder – permanently delete files and folders, so use them carefully.

9. cat file.txt – displays a file’s contents.

10. grep "text" file.txt – searches for text inside a file.

11. chmod – changes permissions. For example, chmod +x script.sh makes a script executable.
